n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Banna,_Ilocos_Norte"}
{"title_page": "Midwest High Speed Rail Association", "text_new": "{{Infobox organization\n| name   = High Speed Rail Alliance\n| logo   = Midwest high speed rail logo.jpg\n| type   = [[501(c)#501(c)(3)|Non-profit]]\n| founded_date      = 1993\n| location          = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]] United States\n| key_people        = [[Rick Harnish|Richard Harnish]], Executive Director\n| area_served       = [[Midwest|Midwest United States]]\n| product           =\n| mission           = \n| focus             = \n| method            = \n| revenue           = \n| endowment         = \n| num_volunteers    = \n| num_employees     = \n| num_members       = \n| subsid            = \n| owner             = \n| Non-profit_slogan = \n| homepage          = [http://www.hsrail.org hsrail.org]\n}}\n\nThe '''High Speed Rail Alliance''' ('''HSRA''') (until late 2019, named the '''Midwest High Speed Rail Association''' ('''MHSRA''')) was founded in 1993 and is based in [[Chicago, Il|Chicago]], [[Illinois]]. The association is a non-profit, member-supported organization that primarily advocates for world-class 220-mph high-speed trains linking major Midwestern cities and supports fast, frequent and dependable trains on other routes that connect with 220-mph corridors to form a modern regional and national rail network.<ref>[http://www.hsrail.org/what-we-do.org/home ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714225305/http://www.midwesthsr.org/home |date=July 14, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=112561131 |title=Midwestern States All Aboard High-Speed-Rail Push |publisher=NPR.org |date=2009-09-04 |accessdate=2015-03-18}}</ref>\n\nThe High Speed Rail Alliance's executive director, [[Rick Harnish|Richard Harnish]], believes it is time for America to \u201ccatch up\u201d with European and Asian countries in terms of using high-speed rail systems.<ref name=\"nbcchicago1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local-beat/chicago-st-louis-high-speed-train-rail-063009.html |title=Chicago to St. Louis in 2 Hours? |publisher=Nbcchicago.com |date= |accessdate=2015-03-18}}</ref>\n\nThe Association is an active member of fourbillion.com, a coalition of advocacy organizations that worked to secure a $4&nbsp;billion appropriation in 2010 for high-speed rail in the U.S. The effort began after the US House of Representatives passed a bill that included $4&nbsp;billion for high-speed rail. The Senate cut the allocation down to $1.2&nbsp;billion in their version. The two bills were in a conference committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fourbillion.com/ |title=Nonprofit Management Software, Nonprofit Fundraising Software |publisher=Fourbillion.com |date= |accessdate=2015-03-18}}</ref> In June 2009, The High Speed Rail Alliance released a transportation engineering study of a 220-mph rail corridor in the Midwest. The 220-mph high-speed link would cut the trip from Chicago to St. Louis to 1 hour and 52 minutes and also serve [[Ohare International Airport|O'Hare International Airport]] as well as key Illinois business, university and government centers in [[Kankakee, Il|Kankakee]], [[Champaign, Il|Champaign]], [[Decatur, Il|Decatur]], [[Springfield, Il|Springfield]] and [[Edwardsville, Il|Edwardsville]]. The line would cost between 12&nbsp;billion and 13&nbsp;billion dollars.<ref name=\"nbcchicago1\"/>\n\nThe HSRA views the Chicago-St. Louis link as the first of a regional 220-mph high-speed rail network that would link [[Chicago, Il|Chicago]], [[St. Louis, Mo|St. Louis]], the [[Twin Cities, Minnesota|Twin Cities]], [[Milwaukee, Wi|Milwaukee]], [[Detroit Michigan|Detroit]], [[Indianapolis, in|Indianapolis]], [[Cincinnati OH|Cincinnati]], [[Cleveland, oh|Cleveland]], [[Columbus, oh|Columbus]] and [[Pittsburgh, Pa|Pittsburgh]], putting more than 35&nbsp;million people within a three-hour train ride of Chicago.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://midwesthsr.org/vision |title=The Vision &#124; Midwest High Speed Rail Association |publisher=Midwesthsr.org |date= |accessdate=2015-03-18}}</ref>\n\nIn a proposal to the U.S. Department of Transportation, SNCF, operator of the TGV high-speed rail network in France, estimated that a Midwestern 220-mph high-speed rail network would create 677,000 permanent jobs and 316,000 construction jobs. Automobile trips would be reduced by 4.3&nbsp;billion vehicle miles each year, saving 3&nbsp;million barrels of oil each year, and additionally reduce CO<sub>2</sub> and other pollutant emissions by 1.4&nbsp;million tons in 2030. The total estimated cost for the network is $68.5&nbsp;billion.<ref>[http://www.thetransportpolitic.com/sncf/Midwest.pdf SNCF proposal for development of Midwest High Speed Rail Corridor]</ref> Advocates for high-speed rail put that cost in perspective by pointing out that the Interstate Highway System cost 450&nbsp;billion in 2008 dollars.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/opinion/columnist/neuharth/2006-06-22-interstates_x.htm |title=Traveling interstates is our sixth freedom |publisher=Usatoday.com |date=2006-06-22 |accessdate=2015-03-18}}</ref>\n\nThe High Speed Rail Alliance has been a vocal critic of libertarian and conservative activists who view HSRA as distorting the record and facts on high-speed rail. In July 2009, it released a document<ref>{{cite web|url=http://midwesthsr.org/fact-vs-fiction |title=Fact vs. Fiction &#124; Midwest High Speed Rail Association |publisher=Midwesthsr.org |date= |accessdate=2015-03-18}}</ref> responding to statements by the [[Cato Institute]] and the Reason Foundation about high-speed rail.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Chicago Hub Network]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.hsrail.org}}\n\n[[Category:High-speed rail in the United States]]\n[[Category:Rail advocacy organizations in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{update|reason=The 2020 mph rail speed did not become reality (it's 110 mph) Now what does MHSRA think?|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name   = High Speed Rail Alliance\n| logo   = Midwest high speed rail logo.jpg\n| type   = [[501(c)#501(c)(3)|Non-profit]]\n| founded_date      = 1993\n| location          = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]] United States\n| key_people        = [[Rick Harnish|Richard Harnish]], Executive Director\n| area_served       = [[Midwest|Midwest United States]]\n| product           =\n| mission           = \n| focus             = \n| method            = \n| revenue           = \n| endowment         = \n| num_volunteers    = \n| num_employees     = \n| num_members       = \n| subsid            = \n| owner             = \n| Non-profit_slogan = \n| homepage          = [http://www.hsrail.org hsrail.org]\n}}\n\nThe '''High Speed Rail Alliance''' ('''HSRA''') (formerly called the '''Midwest High Speed Rail Association''' ('''MHSRA''')) was founded in 1993 and is based in [[Chicago, Il|Chicago]], [[Illinois]]. The association is a non-profit, member-supported organization that primarily advocates for world-class 220-mph high-speed trains linking major Midwestern cities and supports fast, frequent and dependable trains on other routes that connect with 220-mph corridors to form a modern regional and national rail network.<ref>[http://www.hsrail.org/what-we-do.org/home ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714225305/http://www.midwesthsr.org/home |date=July 14, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=112561131 |title=Midwestern States All Aboard High-Speed-Rail Push |publisher=NPR.org |date=2009-09-04 |accessdate=2015-03-18}}</ref>\n\nThe High Speed Rail Alliance's executive director, [[Rick Harnish|Richard Harnish]], believes it is time for America to \u201ccatch up\u201d with European and Asian countries in terms of using high-speed rail systems.<ref name=\"nbcchicago1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local-beat/chicago-st-louis-high-speed-train-rail-063009.html |title=Chicago to St. Louis in 2 Hours? |publisher=Nbcchicago.com |date= |accessdate=2015-03-18}}</ref>\n\nThe Association is an active member of fourbillion.com, a coalition of advocacy organizations that worked to secure a $4&nbsp;billion appropriation in 2010 for high-speed rail in the U.S. The effort began after the US House of Representatives passed a bill that included $4&nbsp;billion for high-speed rail. The Senate cut the allocation down to $1.2&nbsp;billion in their version. The two bills were in a conference committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fourbillion.com/ |title=Nonprofit Management Software, Nonprofit Fundraising Software |publisher=Fourbillion.com |date= |accessdate=2015-03-18}}</ref> In June 2009, The High Speed Rail Alliance released a transportation engineering study of a 220-mph rail corridor in the Midwest. The 220-mph high-speed link would cut the trip from Chicago to St. Louis to 1 hour and 52 minutes and also serve [[Ohare International Airport|O'Hare International Airport]] as well as key Illinois business, university and government centers in [[Kankakee, Il|Kankakee]], [[Champaign, Il|Champaign]], [[Decatur, Il|Decatur]], [[Springfield, Il|Springfield]] and [[Edwardsville, Il|Edwardsville]]. The line would cost between 12&nbsp;billion and 13&nbsp;billion dollars.<ref name=\"nbcchicago1\"/>\n\nThe HSRA views the Chicago-St. Louis link as the first of a regional 220-mph high-speed rail network that would link [[Chicago, Il|Chicago]], [[St. Louis, Mo|St. Louis]], the [[Twin Cities, Minnesota|Twin Cities]], [[Milwaukee, Wi|Milwaukee]], [[Detroit Michigan|Detroit]], [[Indianapolis, in|Indianapolis]], [[Cincinnati OH|Cincinnati]], [[Cleveland, oh|Cleveland]], [[Columbus, oh|Columbus]] and [[Pittsburgh, Pa|Pittsburgh]], putting more than 35&nbsp;million people within a three-hour train ride of Chicago.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://midwesthsr.org/vision |title=The Vision &#124; Midwest High Speed Rail Association |publisher=Midwesthsr.org |date= |accessdate=2015-03-18}}</ref>\n\nIn a proposal to the U.S. Department of Transportation, SNCF, operator of the TGV high-speed rail network in France, estimated that a Midwestern 220-mph high-speed rail network would create 677,000 permanent jobs and 316,000 construction jobs. Automobile trips would be reduced by 4.3&nbsp;billion vehicle miles each year, saving 3&nbsp;million barrels of oil each year, and additionally reduce CO<sub>2</sub> and other pollutant emissions by 1.4&nbsp;million tons in 2030. The total estimated cost for the network is $68.5&nbsp;billion.<ref>[http://www.thetransportpolitic.com/sncf/Midwest.pdf SNCF proposal for development of Midwest High Speed Rail Corridor]</ref> Advocates for high-speed rail put that cost in perspective by pointing out that the Interstate Highway System cost 450&nbsp;billion in 2008 dollars.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/opinion/columnist/neuharth/2006-06-22-interstates_x.htm |title=Traveling interstates is our sixth freedom |publisher=Usatoday.com |date=2006-06-22 |accessdate=2015-03-18}}</ref>\n\nThe High Speed Rail Alliance has been a vocal critic of libertarian and conservative activists who view HSRA as distorting the record and facts on high-speed rail. In July 2009, it released a document<ref>{{cite web|url=http://midwesthsr.org/fact-vs-fiction |title=Fact vs. Fiction &#124; Midwest High Speed Rail Association |publisher=Midwesthsr.org |date= |accessdate=2015-03-18}}</ref> responding to statements by the [[Cato Institute]] and the Reason Foundation about high-speed rail.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Chicago Hub Network]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.hsrail.org}}\n\n[[Category:High-speed rail in the United States]]\n[[Category:Rail advocacy organizations in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Dreulandb", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Midwest_High_Speed_Rail_Association"}
